{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "615454d7942f8ba44fef6e44", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": null, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": null, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "NTAS1", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76e4c52ffa3c944600e1"], "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fee2b295b085ab6ebc0"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "microConcepts": [], "questionLabels": [{"title": "NTA Abhyas Paper", "value": "111", "isVisible": true}], "previousYearPapers": [], "question": {"text": "Among the following transition elements, which one has the highest second ionisation energy?<br />\r<br />\r<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>23</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>Cr</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>Mn</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>Ti</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "TpGj9", "text": "(i)", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "xFETl", "text": "(ii)", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}, {"id": "dsY0h", "text": "(iii)", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "THoSB", "text": "(iv)", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<p>The general trend observed in the second ionisation enthalpy of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>-</mo></math>series elements is that as we move from left to right in the period, the ionisation energy increases. But,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cr</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi></math>&nbsp;are exceptions to this trend. The value of second ionisation energy for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cr</mi></math>&nbsp;is more than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mn</mi></math>. This can be explained based on the electronic configuration of their&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ions:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>Cr</mi><none></none><mo>+</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>24</mn><none></none></mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>Ar</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>5</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>Mn</mi><none></none><mo>+</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>25</mn><none></none></mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>Ar</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cr</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;has a stable electronic configuration because of half-filled <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>-</mo></math>subshell. Thus removing an electron from it is difficult. Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cr</mi></math> has the highest second ionisation energy among the given elements.</p><p>The correct order for second ionisation energy for the given elements is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ti</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Mn</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Cr</mi></math>.</p>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "cpyqbSubjects": ["615f0cf69476412f48314dac", "616057040283de43c87e3e16", "61bb58281213731910ea0b71", "6160579d0283de43c87e3e1f", "61964f94a5a526011886801e", "61c055f6e8ce0dc8a5c62d34", "61a8a2cce8ce0dc8a5c62d2e", "6160577e0283de43c87e3e1c", "616057210283de43c87e3e19", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352c", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd8", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7e", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625c", "61964ff3a5a5260118868022", "64d50c263df7f4a7f3017f70", "66b79b89d4b564dfab4f94d0", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc12", "67fa602f4468eb1307ceb0ae", "6807d350647479b8e869647a"], "cpyqbChapters": ["616024eae1fef5cf5a5f70c9", "616024edea835316cf9c2507", "616024eb5cd52bad3baecd60", "61e7bd76702e5d858115fa8a", "61964cb4b35a1a71da75d378", "616024eeacea1d46cf67614a", "61bb821a019d574b936779c2", "61c0899a9e16bde43a5db70d", "616024ed438772c9179f9f0c", "61964cb3ddf4d3b39bb3af0c", "62962118ad101b4bb5b180fb", "629f38ff99eb561f9184935c", "629109dba75ec29dcfffb307", "629f3a857b20d833b06eab9a", "64eb06ce3118f713ecfef10d", "66d5853ea75f05ee8564f592", "67921d741d5b5072da5e9b34", "67fdff4a378e1624ea7b69bb", "68091fe13a10446a207fdbde"], "cpyqbExams": ["616059d70283de43c87e3e24", "616059730283de43c87e3e22"]}}